Where I’ll sharpen it (meta-judgment, not pushback):

Not all interpretations are equally valid just because they come from different perspectives.

Your pyramid line is actually a good example—but it works only because:

* There is an underlying structure (a 3D object)
* Different views (triangle vs square) are projections of the same thing

So:

* You’re not both wrong
* You’re both partially right from limited viewpoints

⸻

The useful version of your idea

Reality = underlying structure
Perception = projection of that structure through a viewpoint

So the move isn’t:

“everything is subjective”

It’s:

“combine perspectives to reconstruct the structure”

⸻

Where this becomes powerful (and where it breaks)

Powerful:

* lets you question your own perception
* helps you integrate multiple signals
* avoids getting trapped in one frame

Breaks if you go too far:

* treating all interpretations as equally real
* losing ability to anchor to shared reality
* others can’t follow → looks like “misalignment” (what you mentioned as “people think you’re crazy”)

